List Methods in Python
What are List Methods?

List methods are built-in functions used to add, remove, update, or arrange elements in a list.

Lists are mutable, so these methods modify the original list.

1ï¸âƒ£ append()

Adds an element at the end of the list.

numbers = [1, 2, 3]
numbers.append(4)
print(numbers)

Output:

[1, 2, 3, 4]
2ï¸âƒ£ insert()

Adds an element at a specific index.

numbers = [1, 2, 3]
numbers.insert(1, 10)
print(numbers)
3ï¸âƒ£ extend()

Adds multiple elements to a list.

a = [1, 2]
b = [3, 4]

a.extend(b)
print(a)
4ï¸âƒ£ remove()

Removes a specific value.

numbers = [1, 2, 3, 2]
numbers.remove(2)
print(numbers)

(Removes first occurrence)

5ï¸âƒ£ pop()

Removes element using index (default = last).

numbers = [10, 20, 30]
numbers.pop()
print(numbers)
6ï¸âƒ£ clear()

Removes all elements from the list.

numbers = [1, 2, 3]
numbers.clear()
print(numbers)
7ï¸âƒ£ index()

Returns index of an element.

numbers = [10, 20, 30]
print(numbers.index(20))
8ï¸âƒ£ count()

Counts occurrences of an element.

numbers = [1, 2, 2, 3]
print(numbers.count(2))
9ï¸âƒ£ sort()

Sorts list in ascending order.

numbers = [4, 1, 3, 2]
numbers.sort()
print(numbers)
ğŸ”Ÿ reverse()

Reverses the list.

numbers = [1, 2, 3]
numbers.reverse()
print(numbers)
